A oxysterol that is cholesterol in which the hydrogen at the 4beta position has been replaced by a hydroxy group. A metabolite of cholesterol formed by the drug-metabolizing enzyme cytochrome P450 3A4, it is one of the major oxysterols in the human circulation.
An oxysterol that is cholesterol carrying two additional hydroxy groups at the 4beta and 7alpha positions.
An N-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the N-acyl group is specified as (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoyl.
Any ceramide in which the acyl group carries a hydroxy substituent at position 2.
Any polychlorobiphenyl with molecular formula C12H3Cl7.
A dipalmitoyl phosphatidylglycerol in which the stereocentre of the acylated glycerol portion has R-configuration.
An N-acylphosphatidylethanolamine in which the N-acyl group is specified as arachidonoyl while the phosphatidyl acyl groups are both specified as oleoyl.
A member of the class of pyrroles carrying a 2-amino-3-chlorophenyl substituent at position 3.
A member of the class of pyrroles carrying chloro and 2-amino-3-chlorophenyl substituents at positions 3 and 4 respectively.
A 1,2-diglyceride in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as decanoyl and oleoyl respectively.

A branched amino pentasaccharide comprising a linear tetrasaccharide chain of N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosamine, beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine and N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosamine residues linked (1->3), (1->4) and (1->3) respectively, with an alpha-L-fucose residue linked (1->2) to the galactose residue.

A linear amino pentasaccharide comprising N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosamine, N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosamine, alpha-D-galactose, beta-D-galactose and beta-D-glucose residues linked sequentially (1->3), (1->3), (1->4) and (1->4).
